lamic University IMSIU-DDRSP2502 pmc-status-qastatus 0 pmc-status-live yes pmc-status-embargo no pmc-status-released yes pmc-prop-open-access yes pmc-prop-olf no pmc-prop-manuscript no pmc-prop-legally-suppressed no pmc-prop-has-pdf yes pmc-prop-has-supplement no pmc-prop-pdf-only no pmc-prop-suppress-copyright no pmc-prop-is-real-version no pmc-prop-is-scanned-article no pmc-prop-preprint no pmc-prop-in-epmc yes issue-copyright-statement © BioMed Central Ltd., part of Springer Nature 2025 Introduction The COVID-19 pandemic, caused by the SARS-CoV-2 virus, has created unprecedented challenges for global public health, resulting in millions of infections and deaths worldwide. While many infected individuals experience mild symptoms, a substantial proportion develop severe complications, notably COVID-19 pneumonia and COVID-19-associated pulmonary aspergillosis (CAPA). Both conditions are critical determinants of COVID-19-related morbidity and mortality, especially among hospitalised patients and those in intensive care units. COVID-19 pneumonia often presents with severe respiratory distress requiring urgent intervention, while CAPA, a secondary fungal infection, frequently occurs in critically ill, mechanically ventilated patients, complicating diagnosis and management. Severe COVID-19 pneumonia [ 1 2 3 4 CAPA has been increasingly recognised as a serious secondary infection during severe COVID-19 illness, with important implications for patient prognosis. Pierre Bay et al. [ 5 6 7 The link between severe pneumonia and CAPA is well-established, underscoring the importance of vigilant monitoring in high-risk COVID-19 patients. Retrospective observational studies [ 8 9 Mathematical modelling has played a pivotal role in deepening our understanding of COVID-19 transmission dynamics and its associated complications, offering valuable predictive insights that support effective public health decision-making. Such models, ranging from classic compartmental structures such as SIR, SEIR, and their numerous extensions, to more advanced data-driven and stochastic approaches, allow researchers to capture key aspects of disease spread and progression within a population. Beyond COVID-19, similar modelling techniques have been successfully applied to a wide range of infectious diseases, including TB [ 10 11 12 13 14 15 \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
