				\begin{document}$$R_0$$\end{document} Studies [ 19 21 In the specific context of COVID-19, mathematical models have been instrumental in assessing viral spread patterns, quantifying the impact of non-pharmaceutical interventions (NPIs) such as social distancing, mask mandates, and mobility restrictions, and determining the optimal timing and allocation of pharmaceutical measures such as vaccination campaigns and antiviral treatments. These models also facilitate scenario analysis and forecasting based on real epidemiological data, enabling governments and health authorities to prepare healthcare resources, design tailored policies, and evaluate intervention trade-offs under uncertainty. Furthermore, by incorporating real-time data streams and accounting for stochastic variability, they improve the robustness of predictions and adapt to changing epidemiological conditions, which is particularly important in the face of emerging variants and evolving public health guidelines. Optimal control theory provides a rigorous and quantitative framework for designing intervention strategies that aim to minimise disease burden while respecting economic and logistical constraints. In epidemiology, this approach formulates models with time-dependent control variables—such as vaccination, enhanced hospitalisation, and targeted treatment—to achieve specific public health outcomes, including reduced transmission and mortality. Recent advances illustrate its versatility: Zeb et al. [ 22 23 24 18 25 27 28 Novelty of the study This study introduces a novel compartmental model—the \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
