				\begin{document}$$R_0$$\end{document} To evaluate intervention strategies, we incorporated an optimal control framework comprising vaccination, hospitalisation encouragement, and enhanced treatment of hospitalised patients. Numerical simulations of single-, double-, and triple-control strategies demonstrated that the combined application of all three control measures is substantially more effective in reducing disease burden than any subset alone. This finding underscores the critical importance of multifaceted, integrated approaches to manage severe COVID-19 complications and fungal co-infections comprehensively. Limitations of the study Despite offering a comprehensive framework to study the co-dynamics of COVID-19 pneumonia and CAPA, the present study has certain limitations. First, the model does not include an explicit vaccinated compartment; instead, vaccination is modeled as a time-dependent control variable. This choice simplifies the model and reflects the limited availability of stratified vaccination data during the studied period (March 2020 to April 2021). As a result, the long-term immunity conferred by vaccination is not explicitly tracked. CAPA cases are not directly observed in public epidemiological datasets. Hence, their progression is modeled using literature-derived parameter values rather than real-time CAPA-specific data. This approach captures general trends but may not reflect regional variations in fungal complications. The model assumes a homogeneous population without accounting for age structure or comorbidities, which are known to significantly affect the risk of severe COVID-19 outcomes and CAPA. Incorporating such heterogeneity could improve the precision of predictions. Additionally, several parameter values are based on estimates from existing studies due to the unavailability of precise localized clinical data. This may introduce uncertainty in parameter sensitivity and policy recommendations. This study does not currently include a full out-of-sample or external validation due to data constraints. Future work will apply the model to different time periods or regional datasets to assess generalisability and predictive robustness. Finally, Although the model includes epidemiologically-grounded compartments and parameters, it does not incorporate detailed mechanistic biological or immunological processes, which limits physical realism at the molecular or cellular levels. Clinical and epidemiological relevance of the model Our current model primarily captures the interaction between COVID-19 pneumonia and COVID-19-associated pulmonary aspergillosis (CAPA), but its applicability to patients with advanced cancers, immunological disorders, or prolonged viral persistence remains an important extension. Patients with advanced cancer or hematological malignancies are particularly vulnerable to severe SARS-CoV-2 infection Due to impaired immune homeostasis and anticancer therapies, with reported 30-day COVID-19-related mortality rates between 13% and 33%, markedly higher than the 0.5%–2% observed in the general population [ 52 53 54 \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
