				\begin{document}$$\omega$$\end{document} Concluding remarks In conclusion, this integrated modeling and control analysis provides valuable insights into the dynamics, clinical complexity, and mitigation of COVID-19 pneumonia and CAPA. The results advocate for combined vaccination, timely hospitalisation, and effective treatment strategies to reduce both disease transmission and clinical severity. The expanded discussion emphasizes the model’s adaptability to diverse clinical scenarios and evolving viral landscapes, reinforcing its utility as a decision-support tool in ongoing and future respiratory infectious disease management. Future research may explore incorporating further clinical heterogeneity, molecular mechanisms, and comprehensive cost-effectiveness analyses to inform optimized intervention implementation. Abbreviations CAPA COVID-19-Associated Pulmonary Aspergillosis CARDS COVID-19-Associated Acute Respiratory Distress Syndrome COVID-19 Coronavirus Disease 2019 ICU Intensive Care Unit PRCC Partial Rank Correlation Coefficient LHS Latin Hypercube Sampling DFE Disease-Free Equilibrium EE Endemic Equilibrium ODE Ordinary Differential Equation E RMSE Error Root Mean Square Error E MAE Error Mean Absolute Error R 0 Basic Reproduction Number S Susceptible individuals I Infected individuals I cp COVID-19 Pneumonia individuals I ca CAPA-infected individuals H Hospitalized individuals R Recovered individuals T Time Publisher's Note Springer Nature remains neutral with regard to jurisdictional claims in published maps and institutional affiliations. Acknowledgements The authors sincerely thank the editor and anonymous reviewers for their valuable comments and suggestions, which greatly helped in improving the quality of this manuscript. Clinical trial Not applicable. Authors' contributions M.A.R.: Conceptualization, Methodology, Software, Validation, Formal Analysis, Investigation, Data Curation, Writing – Original Draft, Writing – Review & Editing, Supervision